Maghsoodloo, Parham - Carlsen, M., 0-1, World Rapid 2023, https://lichess.org/kOjDWfiG } { [%cal Gf6g7] }) 10... d4!? { Again, Sindarov shows a lot of determination to fight for more than equality. } { [%clk 1:50:41] } (10... Be7 { Was the calmer option. }) 11. Bxf6 { [%clk 1:28:24] } (11. O-O-O e5 12. Nd5 Be6 { Transposing to the Nepo game. }) 11... Qxf6 { Capture made after almost 20 minutes. Black evaluated, correctly, that capturing the pawn would not have led to the same position played by Nepo (as shown in the analysis). } { [%clk 1:31:52] } (11... gxf6?! 12. O-O-O e5 13. Bd3 $14 { White's knight can stay on c3 longer and even maneuver through e2-g3 to exploit Black's weaknesses in a better way. } { [%csl Rc3][%cal Gc3e2,Ge2g3] }) 12. Ne4 { [%clk 1:26:51] } 12... Qf5 { [%clk 1:31:47] } 13. b4 { Pragg goes for it all. } { [%clk 1:13:12] } (13. Bd3!? { White had the option of going for this very interesting move. } 13... dxe3 14. O-O exf2+ 15. Kh1 { The position is definitely unclear, but considering Sindarov's style, I would say that he would feel a lot more comfortable in this position. He is the one under pressure. } { [%cal Gc2h7,Gf1f2,Ge4c5,Ge4d6] }) 13... Nxb4!? { Challenge accepted. Despite the position being very complicated, I could definitely imagine Sindarov feeling comfortable in this situation.
From this point on, we will see white trying to hold and find a safe shelter while Black creates constant difficulties. } { [%clk 1:15:50] } (13... Be7!? { Despite losing a pawn, this move offers Black an okay position as we will explore. } 14. b5 (14. exd4 a5 15. b5 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 Qe5 $44 { Black position is super promising. } { [%cal Ge5a1,Ge5e1] }) 14... Ne5 15. Nxd4 Qg6 { The compensation is clear, due to the piece activity, dark weak squares and White's c4 pawn. } { [%cal Bc8d7,Ba8c8] }) 14. axb4 { [%clk 1:12:08] } 14... Bxb4+ { [%clk 1:15:46] } 15. Kd1 { [%clk 1:05:37] } 15... dxe3 { [%clk 1:03:27] } 16. Bd3 { [%clk 0:59:52] } (16. fxe3 b5! { Black need to make things happen } 17. Bd3 (17. cxb5 Bb7 18. Bd3 Rac8 $36) 17... bxc4 18. Qxc4 a5 { The engine is always saying White should be ok, but from a human standpoint, this position is very difficult to play. } { [%cal Gc8a6,Gf5f6,Gf6a1,Ge8d8,Gd8d1] }) 16... Qg6! { Always creating threats, Sindarov is not going to make it easy for Pragg } { [%clk 1:01:54] } 17. fxe3 { [%clk 0:37:06] } (17. Ng3 f5 18. fxe3 Qf6 $36) 17... f5 { [%clk 1:00:13] } 18. Ng3 { [%clk 0:34:50] } 18... Bc5 { [%clk 0:56:49] } (18... Qf6!? { Same idea, but maybe a bit more accurate. } 19. Ke2 Bc5) 19. Qc3?! { This is a turning point. Pragg tried Qc3 to prevent Black from playing e5, but it will not work as shown. Better was: } { [%clk 0:30:42] } (19. e4! Qf6 (19... f4 20. e5 $16) 20. Ra2) 19... e5! $15 { Again: the kid never misses. As it occured against Esipenko, Sindarov shows his world-class sense for initiative. } { [%clk 0:50:37] } 20. Bc2 { [%clk 0:24:07] } (20. Nxe5 Qf6) 20... e4 { [%clk 0:49:49] } 21. Nd2! { Very good defense by Pragg. The natural 21.Nd4 wasn't as good } { [%clk 0:21:55] } (21. Nd4 f4 22. Nge2 (22. exf4 Rd8) 22... Bg4 $36 { Black's initiative looks more than dangerous. }) 21... Rd8 { [%clk 0:36:02] } 22. Kc1 { [%clk 0:20:21] } 22... Qg5 { [%clk 0:31:23] } 23. Re1 { [%clk 0:19:24] } 23... Qe7 { [%clk 0:27:10] } (23... a5!? { An interesting option. Black sacs a pawn and let White trade rooks for the long-term attack. } { [%cal Gc5b4] } 24. Rxa5 Rxa5 25. Qxa5 b6 26. Qc3 Qe7 $36 { [%cal Gc8e6,Gc5b4,Gd8a8,Gd8d2,Ga8a1] }) 24. Re2?! { Very natural but not precise. It was better for White to play: } { [%clk 0:15:04] } (24. Rd1 { [%csl Re3] } 24... Bb4 25. Qb2 f4 $36 { I'm pretty sure this was the position Pragg visualized and indeed looks dangerous. Apparently, White should hold after } { [%cal Gc8g4] } 26. exf4 Bg4 27. Ndxe4! Bxd1 28. Bxd1 { With 2 pieces for the R and a very exposed K, White should hold. Honestly, it is too hard to perceive that far away. And for regular GMs like me, it is even hard to find it with the position in front of my eye and engine on :) }) 24... Bb4 { [%clk 0:19:26] } 25. Qb2 { [%clk 0:14:55] } 25... a5 $17 { Another great move by Sindarov. He doesn't rush and understands that, even by taking some time to bring his pieces, White is not going to find an easy defense. } { [%cal Ga8a6] [%clk 0:10:04] } 26. Nb3 { [%clk 0:08:59] } 26... Ra6 { [%clk 0:09:48] } 27. Nd4 { [%clk 0:08:18] } 27... Qg5?! { Maybe his first innacuracy, if we could call it. } { [%clk 0:08:07] } (27... g6 { The engine suggests that is better to keep the Q a bit more flexible on e7. }) 28. Kb1 { [%clk 0:06:18] } 28... h5!? { He is not planning to let Pragg relax, Black creates more and more threats. } { [%clk 0:06:08] } 29. Ka2 { This is a key moment. With time scramble approaching, Pragg had the difficult task of holding a difficult position. As we know, attacking is always easier than defending. For this reason, a good attempt was probably to go for the following: } { [%clk 0:05:15] } (29. Rf2 g6 (29... Qxe3 30. Ndxf5 { [%cal Gb2g7] }) 30. Qc1 Bc3 (30... h4 31. Nge2) 31. Ra3 { With very good chances, despite losing a third pawn. } { [%cal Ga3b3] }) 29... h4 { [%clk 0:05:31] } 30. Nf1 { [%clk 0:05:03] } 30... Bd7 { [%clk 0:05:05] } 31. Rd1 { [%clk 0:04:44] } 31... Rc8 { [%clk 0:05:01] } 32. Nd2 { [%clk 0:04:05] } 32... Rb6! { After playing very natural moves, Sindarov manages to create some concrete difficulties with less than 5 minutes on the clock! } { [%clk 0:04:43] } 33. c5?? { Sadly, Pragg will not be able to activate his pieces well enough. } { [%clk 0:03:23] } (33. g4!? { Honestly the position is difficult for White, but this would have led to some complications and since Sindarov was also below the 5-min mark, anything could have happened. }) 33... Rxc5?! { [%clk 0:03:41] } (33... Bxc5! 34. Bb3+ Kh7 35. Nc4 Rb4 $19 { Should be over. } { [%cal Ga5a4,Gc5d4,Gc8c4,Gb4c4] }) 34. Qb3+?? { [%clk 0:01:50] } (34. Nc4 Ra6 35. g4!? { In an objectively lost position, this was again a good resource that could have complicated things a bit. }) 34... Kh8 { [%clk 0:03:18] } 35. Qf7 { [%clk 0:01:26] } 35... Rxc2+! $19 { The game is over now. This is probably the detail that Pragg missed while evaluation his 33th move. } { [%clk 0:03:16] } 36. Kb1 { [%clk 0:01:05] } (36. Nxc2 Be6+) 36... Rxd2 { [%clk 0:02:35] } 37. Rdxd2 { [%clk 0:00:51] } 37... Bxd2+ { [%clk 0:02:34] } 38. Ka2 { [%clk 0:00:40] } 38... Bxe3 { [%clk 0:01:46] } 39. Qxd7 { [%clk 0:00:25] } 39... Bxd4 { [%clk 0:01:44] } 40. Qxd4 { [%clk 0:30:47] } 40... Qf6 { 0-1 Black wins.
An epic battle between these two youngsters. On the winning side, Sindarov showed determination right in the opening by going for 9..Re8 and, after accepting Pragg's challenge, sacrificed a piece for long-term initiative to prove it right.
On the other side, a tough blow for Pragg with the white pieces. But definitely one blow that is better to take this early, with plenty of games ahead to recover. As chess fans, we just want to thank their effort and will to put up a great fight! } { [%clk 0:32:10] } 0-1

